pprehending ‘Identity’ and ‘Motivation’ through a Poststructural Lens -- t13. Language Learning Motivation in Asia: Current Trajectory and Possible Future -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book fills an existing gap in language learning motivation research by examining the applications of current motivational theories and models from WEIRD (Western, educated, industrialized, rich, developed) contexts to educational systems in Asian contexts. All chapters are focused on second language (L2) motivation as it applies to the EFL situation in Asian countries where English is a mandatory subject in school. Themes in the volume cover the use of possible L2 selves as a theoretical model of motivation, the role of teacher motivation and demotivation in non-European educational systems, study abroad, motivation among adolescents, cross-cultural differences in learner motivation among Asian cultures and the influence of native speakerism on language motivation and cultural identity. This book will appeal to ESL/EFL educators, postgraduate students, researchers and teacher-trainers both inside and outside Asian countries, who are interested in research on L2 motivation in general and within Asian contexts in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching learningzAsia. 0aLearning, Psychology of. 0aMotivation (Psychology). 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aAsian learners of English.  aComplex dynamic systems.  aDemotivation.  aIdentity.  aL2 motivation.  aL2 self.  aLanguage learning.  aMotivation.  aPossible selves.  aSLA.1 aApple, Matthew T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator